@node intro "Introduction"

 Ok, so I won't say I wrote it because I found no memory-bar that suited me,
 as I did in the AvailMem 1.0 docs... Why? Because I already had a perfectly
 working memorybar (AM 1.0).. So why did I write a 'sequel' to such a
 success? Well, I got some complaints from a friend o' mine who wanted
 online settings, instead of changing the tooltypes everytime he wanted to
 move the window. So I thought, "What the heck", and started to rewrite the
 availmem code. I failed. After 1000 lines of assembly code, I couldn't read
 my own program, and it crashed all the time.. A half year later, I thought
 of learning how to code commodities, and looked at availmem, "Why not make
 availmem a commodity?". At this time, I had understood GadToolsBox, and
 designed a nice little GUI. Thanks to this, I could avoid the trouble with
 designing by code. I divided the code into small sections, linked up with
 defines and a sMakefile. I also 'pre-coded' some stuff in C, to see the
 effects of different things. Now, AvailMem 2 is over 2000 lines of pure
 assembly code, and still fully working with no known bugs.

@endnode

@node require "Requirements"

 AvailMem 2 requires at least V37 (2.0) kickstart and a MC68020. Why?

 I don't know how to multiplicate longwords with only words. :)

 This means a A3000 with V37 (KS 2.0) will safely run AvailMem, but a A500
 with V40 will certainly not.

 Sorry all you A500 owners.. There ARE solutions but i'm to lazy! :) If
 anyone have fast longword multiplication and division routine in mc68000
 assembler I would be grateful!

@endnode
@node changes "Changes"

 Changes from AvailMem 1.0:
 ---------------------------

   - AvailMem now loads as a commodity.

   - Menus! :)

   - More configurable memory-bars. You can now also decide if you want
     to have chip, fast OR public memory displayed in the window.

   - The preferences are built in.

   - The memory-display window is resizable from within the program.

   - No more need to terminate AvailMem when changing displaymodes,
     just select the hide-menuitem in the menu and afterwards press the
     popup-key.

   - You can now flush your memory with a single click on one of the
     memory-bars. VERY useful! (First implemented in the unreleased AM 1.1)

   - Separate configuration-file.

   - The borders can be minimized and even removed, to make AvailMem take
     as little as possible of the screen.

   - The window can be made to always try to stay on top, or, be forced to
     always stay behind all the other windows. (Watch out when setting WB
     to backdrop).

 Things to come:
 ----------------

   - Locale support.

   - IFF-Patterns in window. (Or maybe just one color)

   - User-selectable font.

   - More fontsensitive configuration GUI.

   - More configurable memory-bars. (Render horizontal OR vertical)

   - Your suggestions. I need them! @{"Contact me!" link author}

@endnode

