@node cfg_Tooltypes "Configuration/Program Tooltypes"

 AvailMem v2.0 support the following tooltypes:

   CX_POPKEY    -    Defines a new popupkey to be used.

   CX_POPUP     -    If YES, or not defined, the program window will pop up.

   CFGNAME      -    This is a magic thing :). The name you define will be used as
                     the first name in the configuration-file, and will also be used
                     as the Commodity Handler name, so if you define a different name,
                     you can have several copies of AvailMem running! Please choose
                     a reasonable name (without ':' etc) as i don't scan the string.

@endnode

@node cfg_Colours "Configuration/Colours Selection"

 The two palette-bars select the different colours which display the
 memory-bars.

@endnode

@node cfg_FlushButtons "Configuration/Flush Buttons"

 Enables the flush-button enhancment. What is it, you may ask? Well, enable
 it, and click in one of the memory-bars. You will notice that there is a
 small border rendered around the selected memory-bar. When releasing the
 button, the program will flush your memory from uneccesary libraries
 and etc.

@endnode
@node cfg_Percentage "Configuration/Display Percentage"

 Enables the percentage printing in the middle of the memory-bars.
 The percent-text is font-sensitive, and won't display if the text
 height is larger than the border.

@endnode
@node cfg_Lines "Configuration/Separating Lines"

 Enables the line-rendering between the memory-blocks, seperating them.

@endnode
@node cfg_Types "Configuration/Types"

 The three check-boxes with Chip, Fast and Public is used to enable and
 disable the different memory-bars, for example, enable chip and public,
 and disable fast. Press Ok. You will now see two memory-bars in the
 display-window, the first representing chip-free and the second
 representing the total amount of memory available.

 The last check-box is a bonus for all Executive users. This bar will
 display how much your CPU is used right now.

@endnode

@node cfg_ScreenName "Configuration/Screen Name"

 Preferred public screen. If the screen wasn't found, AvailMem opens on
 the default public screen.

@endnode

@node cfg_Refresh "Configuration/Refresh Rate"

 Controls the delay between every memory-refresh. Notice that the whole
 program will run with the set speed. For example, if you set refresh rate
 to 5 VBL's (5/50th's of a second), the program will run with the 1/5 of
 the speed as with 1 VBL set.

@endnode

@node cfg_WinTitle "Configuration/Window Title"

 Preferred Window Title. Nothing more to say about that. :)

@endnode

@node cfg_Ok "Configuration/Ok button"

 The selected configuration is transferred to the program config-variables.

@endnode

@node cfg_Cancel "Configuration/Cancel button"

 The program ignores checking the config-buttons for changed
 preferences. Note that the program GUI is still refreshed.

@endnode

@node cfg_MinBorders "Configuration/Minimized Borders"

 The window borders minimize, and as a side-effect the window is
 unmoveable.

@endnode

@node cfg_RemBorders "Configuration/Remove Borders"

 The program borders disappear. If you don't select "Minimized Borders"
 aswell, the window-rendering will be UGLY.

@endnode

@node cfg_OnTop "Configuration/Always On Top"

 With this tooltype enabled, the program will try to stay on top of all
 the other windows. If you put a window over AvailMem, it will take
 up to three seconds, and then AvailMem has moved in front of it.

@endnode

@node cfg_Backdrop "Configuration/Go Backdrop"

 This tooltype forces AvailMem to always stay in the background. This is
 possible because the window becomes a backdrop-window. Beware if you
 have the workbench-window as backdrop, switch to normal window and to
 backdrop again. After this, AvailMem is behind the Workbench backdrop.

@endnode

@node bugs "Bugs in AvailMem 2.0"

 Bugs? No!!! I'll call the exterminator! :)

 Known bugs:

  - With some window-sizes, AvailMem refuses to render the memorybars.
  - Sometimes, AvailMem can start generating Alert() messages. This is
    not AvailMem's fault, but that some program that you run trashes
    the memory-tables, resulting in insane memory-tables. MCP-users
    should also get this result (in GuruHistory):

 --------------------------------------------------------------------------
 Date  : Tisdag 12-Mar-97 02:14:31
 Task  : 010FE258 "AvailMem"
 Error : 0100000C (Recoverable)
 By    : ExecLibrary
 Cause : Sanity check on memory list failed during AvailMem(MEMF_LARGEST)
 --------------------------------------------------------------------------
    The problem CAN be fixed, but as i don't want to patch any system
    vectors, the only way out of it is either to reboot OR terminate
    AvailMem. It's advised to reboot anyway, as the memory is corrupted.

 If you find any new bugs in AvailMem, @{"report them!" link author}

@endnode
